In our minds, we never age….at least I don’t. Each year I get a little older, yet inside my @bellhelmets helmet, I am absolutely convincing myself why I should beat these kids (some of which are nearly half my age). 🤣

The Pro Sport and Pro Am classes at the ATV Motocross Nationals are made up of some really talented kids, riders that are the future of the sport. We cover these classes and riders a great deal on the @diggingdeepatvmxpodcast, making it that much more enjoyable to do a little battling with some of them at select races throughout the summer.

But at 30, I still feel like one of them....and at 40, I’ll probably still feel the same way. **Insert Wolf of Wall Street “I’m not leaving” GIF**

What’s my age again? 🤷‍♂️

Grateful to still be living out my childhood dreams.

If you are anything like me, you too have a story of a teacher asking what you aspire to do with your life, only to respond to your answer with something along the lines of "pick a real career" or "how about something realistic".

Well, I'm thirty years old, and I wouldn’t trade my choice for anything. My family and I are doing well thanks to these ATVs and the conversing I do about them — 213+ hours to date on the @diggingdeepatvmxpodcast, in fact.

Here's to another chapter in the story, here’s to 2023! LFG! 💙🤟

I am honored and humbled to have been invited to compete in the ATV Spring Break Showdown at the @deckertrainingfacility next month. With a giant payout and the event being situated right between the ATV Motocross season opener at Daytona and the Gatorback National, it's going to be the place to be for all ATV enthusiasts on second Saturday of March.

Our @diggingdeepatvmxpodcast coverage of the ninth annual Daytona ATV Supercross is the priority this time of year, so a 2000 mile trip on the heels of that craziness may not be in the cards, but I am truly grateful to be thought of, included, and invited to what is shaping up to be an incredible event. I promised the Decker family that, if invited again, I would be sure to come down and participate in future years.

But for now, as an washed-up old pro, it simply feels good to still be thought of as worthy. See you at ATV Motocross National events this spring/summer! THANKFUL 🤟

While prepping for my conversation with Tom Carlson, I came across an interview he did with ATV Scene at Ashtabula’s 50th Anniversary event. In this interview, the TC Racing Engines icon remembers some of the notable riders that he had worked with over the years. In a list that was mostly made up of all-time greats, Tom then mentioned my name before finishing with my favorite rider of all time. I know my name probably doesn’t belong on any list amongst the legends mentioned but, regardless, I couldn’t help but think what the little boy that grew up being infatuated with those ATV racing legends might’ve thought if he heard this 15 or 20 years ago. I cried actual tears when I first stumbled across this clip and, as I type this now, my eyes are welling up again.

The words of a true ATV racing legend. Tom Carlson, famously of TC Racing Engines, joins this week’s episode of the @diggingdeepatvmxpodcast.

Episode 104 goes live this evening wherever podcasts can be acquired, on YouTube, and at diggingdeepatvmx.com. 🥹🤟

So cool to dig this one up! As referenced on this week's episode of the @diggingdeepatvmxpodcast featuring legendary engine builder Tom Carlson.

This TC Racing Engines ad could be found inside ATV Insider magazine in late 2007. And when brought up on the show, Tom was quick to mention the "grand slam". I had won the WPSA National Championship, Neal McGrath won the AMA title, and Wyatt Gann won the Extreme Dirt Track title all on Tom Carlson tuned TC Racing 300ex machines that year.

To this day, I am still proud to have worked so closely with this true ATV racing legend. I'm grateful to call TC a friend.

I am living still.

15 years ago, at Sunset Ridge, I made my 450cc ATV National debut. Having turned 16 just days prior, & not being old enough to make my debut earlier in the season, I was determined to make a splash to ensure that I wouldn't be forgotten by the ATV racing community or any potential sponsors. Competing in the prestigious 16-24 Class, a 2nd on Saturday set me up for a shot at an overall win. However, Mother Nature had other plans & rain forced the cancellation of Sunday's races. My P-2 finish on Saturday became a 3rd overall when the two heats were combined. [However, I did get my first 450 national overall win next time out at PVR.]

I never would receive any calls regarding factory support or any other life-changing opportunities. The truth is, winning or losing my debut likely paled in comparison to the changing landscape of ATV racing, which saw fewer opportunities for riders like me starting in 2008. However, winning DID matter at Redbud 2011, because after securing a couple overall wins & coming ever-so close to landing on the Pro Am podium — a moment with the mic was my opportunity to plea for a little support. The following Monday, a man named Phil Buerster reached out, & that call marked the beginning of an unforgettable journey.

I had only pursued an entire national schedule once before, winning the WPSA National Championship on my 300ex in 2007, but this newfound support helped launch a decade-long pursuit of the ATV Nationals. Along the way, we clinched a couple of National Championships, podiumed Pro Am, went Pro, was awarded Pro Rookie of the Year honors, all before winning a couple more national titles in recent years.

As a kid, I dreamed of becoming a champion like my heroes Doug Gust & Jeremiah Jones. While that specific dream may not have materialized, I am proud of the niche I/Digging Deep carved out in the sport that I love. Every year, as the Sunset Ridge ATV National approaches, I find myself reflecting on the path I've traveled — & this year is no different. If you had shown me a photo like this one 15 years ago, I would have been happy, knowing that I am still living out my dreams to this day.

I am living still. 💙🤟

I love a good blue grooved racetrack, something that was a regular occurrence when I was growing up but has become a rarity at the ATV nationals over the years. I love the diversity that it adds to the series, challenging riders in a different way than your standard whooped-out motocross track.

Speaking of diversity — @sunsetridgemx owner, Bob Pistole, guaranteed a rough one for the weekend ahead at Round 6 of the ATV Motocross National Championship in Walnut, Illinois.

We discussed this topic and much more with @kenhill127, @brandonhoag26, and @nickgennusa15 on the latest episode of the @diggingdeepatvmxpodcast. Available on all your favorite podcast apps, YouTube, diggingdeeppod.com, or via the links in bio/story! 🔥🤘

I told this story on the podium at the conclusion of this one —
 
My first trip to Loretta Lynn’s was in 2004, and I raced the prestigious event for the first time the following year. However, I came ever-so-close to missing the gate drop.
 
I’ll never forget the way that the rise of the revs around me confused me. Next, I heard my dad behind me say “Buddy, get ready! They’re going to go!” into my little helmet.
 
The 30 second board was located in the same spot back then, but that iconic start straight seemed so long to my beloved Blaster and me. I never even saw the board go up, get flipped, or turn sideways.
 
I’ve flashed back to that memory every trip to Loretta’s in the 18 years since. 43 National event overalls wins later, including this one, I’m still just a moto kid with a never-ending passion.
 
Back to the starting line 🤘
